    triggerDescription: 'user has never invested before and wants to know how or where to start',
    instructions: 'Treat this as onboarding, not advising. The goal is one concrete first action, not a comprehensive education.\n1. Establish readiness: confirm they have an emergency fund (at least 1 month of expenses) and no high-interest debt above 8% — if not, address those first\n2. Ask their time horizon: are they investing for something in under 3 years, 3-10 years, or retirement (10+ years)?\n3. Ask if their employer offers a retirement account with any matching contribution — if yes, this is always the first move\n4. Determine their country/region to recommend the appropriate account type (401k/IRA, ISA, RRSP, etc.)\n5. Recommend one specific starting account type and one specific low-cost index fund appropriate to their time horizon (e.g., total market index fund for long horizons)\n6. Tell them exactly what to do: open account at X, contribute Y per month, select fund Z\n7. Explain in one sentence why diversified index funds beat stock-picking for beginners: lower cost, lower risk, historically reliable\n8. Set a 90-day check-in: do not touch the investment; let it compound\nAvoid technical terms without immediate plain-English definitions. One action per response.',
