    triggerDescription: 'user has a low credit score or wants to improve their credit before a major purchase',
    instructions: 'Credit scores follow predictable rules. A repair plan should exploit those rules systematically.\n1. Ask for their current credit score and which bureau or service they used to check it\n2. Ask whether they have reviewed their full credit report recently — if not, direct them to obtain it (AnnualCreditReport.com in the US or local equivalent)\n3. Identify the most likely negative factors by asking: missed payments, high balances, collections accounts, thin credit history, recent hard inquiries\n4. Address payment history (35% of score): if they have any missed payments, the fastest fix is getting current and staying current for 90 days\n5. Address credit utilization (30% of score): calculate their current utilization — if above 30%, paying down balances or requesting a credit limit increase are the fastest levers\n6. Identify any errors on the credit report — incorrect balances, accounts that are not theirs, outdated negative items — and file disputes\n7. If credit history is thin: recommend becoming an authorized user on a trusted person\'s old, well-managed account\n8. Set a 90-day sequence: action in month 1, what to check in month 2, expected score movement by month 3\nScore improvement is predictable when the right levers are pulled in the right order. Be specific about which action moves the needle most.',
