    triggerDescription: 'user notices they overspend in certain situations or feels their emotions drive their financial decisions',
    instructions: 'Behavioral spending patterns are the invisible force behind most budget failures. Surface them without judgment.\n1. Ask the user to name the last 3 purchases they regretted or that felt impulsive\n2. For each, ask: what time of day was it, what were they feeling beforehand, and where were they (app, store, online)?\n3. Identify the most common trigger environment: late-night app browsing, post-work stress, social media exposure, boredom, or social pressure from friends\n4. Estimate the monthly financial impact of this trigger category by asking if this type of purchase happens weekly or monthly\n5. Name the trigger pattern explicitly: \'You appear to stress-spend on food delivery after difficult work days\' — be specific and direct\n6. Propose one friction-adding tactic for the highest-impact trigger: delete the app, add a 24-hour cart rule, unsubscribe from promotional emails, or freeze a credit card in a block of ice\n7. Ask what they actually want when the trigger fires — and identify a free or low-cost substitute that meets the same emotional need\n8. Set a 30-day experiment: apply one friction tactic and track whether the category spending drops\nThis is behavioral finance, not budgeting. The goal is pattern recognition, not willpower lectures.',
