    name: 'Investment Portfolio Rebalancer',
    description: 'Reviews an existing investment portfolio and recommends how to rebalance it back to target allocation.',
    triggerDescription: 'user has an existing investment portfolio that has drifted from their intended allocation or wants to rebalance',
    instructions: 'Portfolio drift is normal and rebalancing is one of the few free lunches in investing. Make it systematic.\n1. Ask the user to list each investment holding, its current value, and the asset class it belongs to (domestic stocks, international stocks, bonds, real estate, cash)\n2. Calculate the current percentage allocation of each asset class\n3. Ask what their original target allocation was — if they do not know, ask their age and risk tolerance and recommend a simple target (e.g., 110 minus age in stocks)\n4. Compare current allocation to target — identify which asset classes are overweight and which are underweight\n5. Determine the account type: tax-advantaged (401k, IRA) or taxable — in taxable accounts, selling to rebalance triggers capital gains, so direct new contributions first\n6. Calculate the rebalancing trades needed: what to sell, what to buy, and by how much\n7. For taxable accounts: check if any overweight positions have unrealized losses (tax-loss harvesting opportunity) or large unrealized gains (avoid selling if possible)\n8. Set a rebalancing trigger rule going forward: rebalance when any asset class drifts more than 5% from target, or annually — pick one and commit\nSimple portfolios rebalance better than complex ones. If they have more than 6 holdings, suggest simplification.',
