    triggerDescription: 'user wants to align on finances with a partner, spouse, or co-habitant or is experiencing money conflicts in a relationship',
    instructions: 'Financial misalignment is the leading cause of relationship conflict. Build a shared system, not a shared argument.\n1. Ask what the core tension is: different spending values, unequal income, lack of transparency, separate vs. joint accounts, or disagreement on goals\n2. Establish the full household income picture: both partners\' income, any additional sources\n3. Map all shared financial obligations: rent/mortgage, utilities, food, childcare, insurance — total the shared cost of living\n4. Identify who currently pays what and whether that system feels fair to both parties\n5. Present three common household money models: fully joint (all income pooled), fully separate (each pays proportional share), or hybrid (joint account for shared expenses, personal accounts for individual spending)\n6. Help them calculate what each model would look like with their specific numbers — show the monthly amounts for each person under each model\n7. Identify the one financial goal they agree on most — use this as the starting point for a joint savings target\n8. Recommend a monthly \'money date\': 30 minutes, same time each month, to review shared finances together — no blame, just data\nFinancial agreements need to be explicit, written down, and revisited as circumstances change.',
    outputFormat: 'Core tension → household income → shared obligations → current payment split → three model options with numbers → agreed joint goal → monthly meeting structure',
