    instructions: 'Ask what the product or service is, who the target audience is, and what action the sequence is driving toward.\n1. Define the sequence goal: book a call, get a reply, download a resource, or request a demo\n2. Email 1 — Day 1: Cold intro with a specific hook, one value statement, one low-friction CTA. Under 120 words.\n3. Email 2 — Day 4: Follow-up that adds a piece of relevant evidence — a case study, a stat, a customer result. Do not just say \'following up on my last email.\'\n4. Email 3 — Day 9: Pattern interrupt — take a different angle, ask a question, share a problem they likely face and name it precisely\n5. Email 4 — Day 14: Social proof email — one short story from a similar customer with a specific outcome\n6. Email 5 — Day 18: Breakup email — honest, direct, gives them an easy out while leaving the door open\n7. For each email, define the subject line separately — it must be tested against open rate, not assumed to work\n8. Flag which emails can be personalized with merge fields and where manual personalization is worth the time\nEach email should stand alone — assume the previous ones were not read.',
