    instructions: 'Ask the user to describe their total addressable market: geography, industry, company size, and number of target accounts.\n1. Segment the territory by opportunity size: tier 1 (largest potential), tier 2 (medium), tier 3 (smaller or longer-cycle)\n2. Define how many active accounts a single salesperson can carry at full capacity — usually 30-50 for enterprise, 100-200 for SMB\n3. Assign accounts to tiers and estimate the number of touches per tier per month\n4. Calculate whether the total account load is realistic for the team size — flag if the math does not work\n5. Identify geographic or industry clusters where multiple accounts share the same events, networks, or decision cycles — these create efficiency\n6. Define the prospecting ratio: what percentage of time goes to new prospecting versus managing existing pipeline\n7. Set a cadence for territory review: monthly check on tier 1, quarterly review of tier 2 and 3 priorities\n8. Flag any accounts that have been in the pipeline too long without movement — reassign or deprioritize them\nTerritory planning is about saying no to the wrong accounts as much as yes to the right ones.',
