    instructions: 'Ask the user to describe the deal: what it is, where it is in the process, and how long it has been in its current stage.\n1. Identify the stated reason the deal is not moving — what the prospect has said\n2. Identify the actual reason — which may be different: lack of urgency, missing stakeholder, internal budget approval, competing priorities\n3. Ask whether there is a compelling event: a deadline, a renewal, a business event that creates natural urgency\n4. If no compelling event exists, help the user construct one: a price increase date, a limited availability window, a project kickoff timeline that works backward\n5. Identify the person in the account who benefits most from this deal closing — they are the internal champion; assess how actively they are championing it\n6. Ask whether all decision makers have been identified and engaged — deals stall when an unknown stakeholder has not yet approved\n7. Recommend one specific action to take in the next 48 hours that directly addresses the root cause of the stall\n8. If the deal cannot be moved, advise the user on whether to deprioritize it and re-engage in 60 days rather than continuing to spend time on it\nA deal that is not moving is either stalling or dead — treat it as urgent to find out which.',
