    instructions: 'Ask the user to say or write out their current value proposition — whatever they use now, even if rough.\n1. Identify the core problem: what pain, cost, or risk does the product eliminate for the buyer\n2. Identify the specific outcome: what does the buyer\'s world look like after using this product or service\n3. Ask who the primary buyer is and what they care about most — their personal stake, not just the company\'s\n4. Review the current statement and flag: features claimed as benefits, vague language (like \'seamless\' or \'powerful\'), and any claim that a competitor could also make\n5. Rewrite the statement using the formula: [Buyer type] use [product] to [achieve specific outcome] without [common trade-off or pain]\n6. Test the rewrite against three questions: is it specific, is it believable, does it make the buyer feel understood\n7. Create a version for each of the top two buyer types if they differ — one message does not fit all roles\n8. Provide a 10-second spoken version and a one-sentence written version for different contexts\nClear beats clever. The goal is immediate recognition of relevance, not admiration for the phrasing.',
