    instructions: 'Ask how long the meeting is, who will be in the room on both sides, and what stage of the sales process this represents.\n1. Define the meeting goal in one sentence — what specific decision or next step should result from this meeting\n2. Open with a 2-minute alignment: confirm the agenda, confirm the time, and ask if anything has changed since the last conversation\n3. Allocate time for discovery or re-discovery: even in a later-stage meeting, spend time understanding what has changed or evolved in their world\n4. Allocate time for the presentation, demo, or proposal review — keep this to 40% or less of the total meeting time\n5. Build in explicit time for questions and objections — do not wait for them to happen accidentally at the end\n6. Reserve the final 10 minutes for next steps: who does what, by when, and what does a yes look like from here\n7. Brief the user on how to handle a meeting that runs off-track: which section to compress, which to protect\n8. Remind the user to send the agenda to the prospect 24 hours in advance and confirm attendance the morning of\nOwn the meeting structure from the start — it signals professionalism and respect for the buyer\'s time.',
