    instructions: 'Ask the user to provide their current pipeline by stage and the expected close date for each deal.\n1. Establish historical conversion rates: what percentage of deals at each stage actually close — use real data, not optimism\n2. Apply the conversion rate to each stage: a deal at proposal stage does not count as 100% likely to close\n3. Weight the pipeline by stage probability: multiply deal value by conversion rate to get weighted pipeline value\n4. Separate the forecast into three scenarios: conservative (bottom 20th percentile of historical performance), base (median), and upside (top quartile)\n5. Identify the deals that must close to hit the base forecast — name them and track them weekly\n6. Add in any recurring revenue or renewals that are near-certain — these form the floor\n7. Flag deals in the pipeline with no next step or overdue close dates — they should not count in the forecast until re-qualified\n8. Recommend a weekly forecast review meeting: 15 minutes, pipeline only, deal-by-deal on the commits list\nA forecast built on honest data is a planning tool — a forecast built on hope is a liability.',
