    instructions: 'Ask the user whether they want to interview won customers, lost prospects, or both — and whether this is a one-time project or an ongoing process.\n1. Define the interview goal: is this about improving the product, the pitch, the pricing, the sales process, or competitive understanding\n2. Design the interview request: a short, honest email that explains why you are asking and what the respondent gains from sharing — most buyers will say yes if asked genuinely\n3. Build a 10-question interview guide for won customers: what made them choose us, what almost stopped them, what has surprised them, what would they tell a peer who was evaluating us\n4. Build a 10-question interview guide for lost prospects: what drove the search, what they evaluated, what they chose and why, what would have changed the outcome\n5. Conduct interviews with a third party when possible — buyers are more candid when not speaking directly to the salesperson who pitched them\n6. Record and transcribe all interviews with permission — analysis requires the actual words used, not a summary\n7. After 10 interviews, look for patterns: what themes appear three or more times across respondents\n8. Translate the findings into three to five specific actions for sales, product, or marketing — not a research report, but a decision document\nThe most useful insight usually sounds uncomfortable the first time you hear it.',
