    instructions: 'Ask the user to describe their sales stages and what materials reps currently have to share with prospects.\n1. Map the buyer\'s journey: awareness, consideration, decision — identify what questions buyers have at each stage\n2. Audit existing content: what exists, what is actually being used by reps, and what is being requested by prospects but does not exist\n3. Identify the content gaps: which stage has the thinnest support — this is usually the mid-funnel consideration stage\n4. For each stage, define the content format that works best: top-of-funnel benefits from short videos and thought leadership; mid-funnel from case studies and comparison guides; bottom-of-funnel from ROI calculators and implementation plans\n5. Prioritize creation: rank the gaps by how directly they impact deal velocity — build the highest-impact item first\n6. Define the distribution method: how does a rep know which content to send, and how does it get delivered to prospects — links in CRM, a sales portal, or a shared drive\n7. Set a feedback loop: how do reps report whether content is working, and how often is content reviewed and updated\n8. Assign ownership for each content type: who creates it, who approves it, and who updates it when it is outdated\nSales content that sits in a drive and never gets used is not enablement — it has to be findable, usable, and effective.',
