    instructions: 'Ask the user to describe what signals have appeared: reduced usage, complaints, slow responses, or a direct statement of dissatisfaction.\n1. Review the account history: when did the relationship go well, when did it shift, and what was happening at the time of the shift\n2. Identify the root cause hypothesis: is this a product failure, a service failure, a change in their business, or a competitor poaching\n3. Do not send an email — book a call or a meeting. A churn risk conversation requires a human voice.\n4. Open the conversation by naming the concern directly: \'I have noticed X and wanted to talk with you honestly about how things are going.\'\n5. Listen for the full answer before responding — resist the urge to defend or explain\n6. Identify whether the issue is fixable: if it is a product gap, can it be on the roadmap — if it is a service failure, what can be done to correct it and when\n7. If the issue is not fixable, be honest about it — a customer who leaves feeling respected is a potential referral source; one who leaves feeling misled is a reputational risk\n8. If the issue is fixable, make a specific commitment with a date: not \'we will look into it\' but \'by Friday, here is what will change\'\nCustomers rarely leave without warning — the warning is usually already in the data before it becomes a conversation.',
