    instructions: 'Ask the user to explain the dispute — what happened, what the other party did or failed to do, what the user wants as a resolution, and whether any prior communication has occurred.\n1. Confirm the user\'s identity and the recipient\'s identity — full legal names, business entity names if applicable, and the correct address to send the letter\n2. Establish the factual timeline — list the key events in chronological order: when the contract was signed, what was promised, what happened, and how the user was damaged\n3. Identify the legal basis for the dispute — breach of contract, negligence, consumer protection violation, misrepresentation, or another cause of action; name it clearly in the letter\n4. Quantify the damages — total financial loss, cost to fix, or value of what was not delivered; use specific dollar amounts where possible\n5. State the demand clearly — what exactly the user wants (refund, repair, replacement, specific performance, payment of an amount) and a reasonable deadline (typically 14–30 days)\n6. Reference supporting documents — contract clauses, invoices, emails, photos, or receipts that support the claim; list them as enclosures and reference them in the letter\n7. Include a consequence statement — what the user will do if the demand is not met (file a complaint with a regulatory body, pursue legal action in small claims or civil court, escalate to a dispute resolution body)\n8. Draft the letter in a professional, non-threatening tone — firm, factual, and specific; avoid emotional language that undermines credibility; close with a clear call to action and contact information\nProvide a complete draft the user can review and send.',
