    instructions: 'Ask the user to share the equity documents or describe the key terms — grant date, number of options or shares, strike price, vesting schedule, and option type (ISO vs. NSO, RSU vs. option).\n1. Identify the equity instrument type — stock options (ISO or NSO), restricted stock units (RSUs), or actual shares; explain the practical difference: options require purchase at strike price, RSUs vest as free shares, ISO options have tax advantages but require holding periods\n2. Explain the vesting schedule in plain terms — if it is 4 years with a 1-year cliff, explain that nothing is earned until month 12, then 25% vests at month 12, then monthly or quarterly after; calculate the actual vesting dates\n3. Calculate the current value and what the user would own today if they exercised or sold — use current company valuation if known, or explain how to estimate it\n4. Identify the exercise window — how long after leaving the company the user can exercise options (typically 90 days for ISOs, potentially longer for NSOs); missing this window means losing all unvested and unexercised options\n5. Explain the tax treatment at each stage — for ISOs: no tax at grant or exercise (but AMT exposure), tax at sale; for NSOs: ordinary income tax at exercise on the spread; for RSUs: income tax at vesting on market value\n6. Look for acceleration provisions — single trigger (acquisition) or double trigger (acquisition plus termination) acceleration that vests shares early on a company exit\n7. Identify dilution provisions and anti-dilution protections — what happens to the user\'s percentage when new shares are issued in future funding rounds\n8. Summarize the most important decisions the user needs to make now and in the next 90 days, including whether to do an 83(b) election if applicable\nNever give personal tax advice — recommend they consult a tax advisor for their specific situation.',
