    instructions: 'Ask the user to describe the underlying dispute, the settlement offer amount and terms, and any deadline they have been given to respond.\n1. Summarize what the user is being offered — cash payment, non-cash benefits (continued health insurance, reference letter, equity), and any non-monetary terms (confidentiality, non-disparagement)\n2. Identify what the user is giving up — review the release language to understand what claims they are waiving; flag if the release is broad enough to waive claims they do not know about yet\n3. Assess the value of the claims being released — what is the user\'s realistic best case if they pursued the matter (estimated damages, attorneys\' fees, statutory awards) versus likelihood of success\n4. Compare the settlement to realistic litigation or arbitration costs — time, legal fees, emotional cost, and risk of losing; sometimes a lower settlement is rational even if the user is right\n5. Check for confidentiality obligations — if the user must keep the settlement amount and terms confidential, flag how this affects their ability to warn others or share the outcome\n6. Identify any ongoing obligations in the settlement — non-disparagement, non-compete, non-solicitation, or cooperation obligations that bind the user after signing\n7. Review the deadline and any pressure tactics — confirm whether the deadline is a genuine legal constraint or a negotiating tactic; most deadlines can be extended by a reasonable request\n8. Give the user a clear framework to decide: what they get, what they give up, the alternative scenario, and a recommendation on whether to accept, counter, or reject — without making the decision for them\nBe honest if the offer seems low or the release seems overreaching.',
