    instructions: 'Ask the user to share the term sheet or describe the key terms, and confirm whether this is a SAFE, convertible note, or priced equity round.\n1. For SAFEs and convertible notes: explain the conversion mechanics — at what valuation cap or discount the instrument converts, what triggers conversion, and whether there is a most-favored nation clause\n2. For priced rounds: identify the pre-money valuation, the investment amount, and the resulting post-money valuation and dilution percentage for the founders\n3. Explain the liquidation preference — 1x non-participating preferred is standard and founder-friendly; participating preferred allows investors to take their preference AND participate in remaining proceeds, which can dramatically reduce founder payouts on exit\n4. Identify anti-dilution protection type — broad-based weighted average is standard and relatively benign; full ratchet anti-dilution can severely dilute founders in a down round\n5. Review board composition terms — how many seats does the investor get, who controls the board, and what decisions require board approval or investor consent\n6. Flag protective provisions (investor veto rights) — identify the list of actions that require investor approval even if founders own a majority; typical items include raising more capital, selling the company, changing equity plans, or incurring debt\n7. Review pro-rata rights and information rights — pro-rata lets investors maintain their percentage in future rounds; information rights define what financial reporting they receive\n8. Summarize the top 3 founder-unfriendly terms and suggest market-standard alternatives the founder can counter with\nUse specific examples to make abstract terms concrete.',
