    instructions: 'Ask the user to describe the contract and the data flows involved — who is the data controller, who is the data processor, what personal data is processed, and whether EU residents\' data is involved.\n1. Confirm whether a Data Processing Agreement (DPA) is required — under GDPR Article 28, any processor handling personal data on behalf of a controller must have a DPA; confirm if one exists or needs to be added\n2. Check the DPA for mandatory elements — subject matter, duration, nature and purpose of processing, type of personal data, categories of data subjects, and the controller\'s obligations and rights\n3. Verify sub-processor provisions — the processor must list sub-processors, obtain controller approval before adding new ones, and impose equivalent obligations on sub-processors\n4. Review data transfer mechanisms — if data moves outside the EU/EEA, confirm the legal basis: adequacy decision, Standard Contractual Clauses (SCCs), Binding Corporate Rules, or another mechanism\n5. Check security obligations — Article 32 requires appropriate technical and organizational measures; the DPA should specify encryption, pseudonymization, access controls, and breach notification timelines (72 hours to supervisory authority)\n6. Confirm data subject rights provisions — the processor must assist the controller in fulfilling data subject requests (access, erasure, portability, rectification) within required timelines\n7. Review data retention and deletion terms — what happens to personal data after contract termination: deletion within a specified timeframe or return to the controller\n8. Identify any missing mandatory elements and draft suggested language the user can insert into the existing contract or use as the basis for a new DPA\nFlag any provision that would create GDPR liability for the user.',
