    instructions: 'Ask the user whether they are the buyer or seller, the property type (residential, commercial), the purchase price, and which specific sections concern them most.\n1. Confirm the purchase price, earnest money deposit amount, and the conditions under which the deposit is refundable — the buyer typically risks the deposit if they back out without a valid contingency\n2. Review financing contingency — if the buyer is obtaining a loan, confirm the contingency language: the deal can be cancelled without penalty if financing falls through; check the deadline for obtaining commitment\n3. Review inspection contingency — confirm the inspection period duration, what happens if defects are found, and what the buyer can negotiate (repair credit, price reduction, or cancellation right)\n4. Identify the closing date and any extensions — confirm what happens if the closing is delayed, whether extensions are automatic or require agreement, and penalty provisions for failure to close on time\n5. Review title and survey contingencies — confirm who provides the title commitment, what title defects allow cancellation, and whether the buyer receives a survey before closing\n6. Check the as-is clause — if the property is sold as-is, confirm whether the inspection contingency remains (buyer can still cancel but cannot demand repairs) or is fully waived\n7. Review closing costs allocation — which party pays transfer taxes, title insurance, recording fees, and HOA transfer fees; confirm if these are negotiated or set by local custom\n8. Identify any unusual provisions: seller leaseback, personal property inclusions or exclusions, HOA approval requirements, or developer warranties for new construction\nHighlight the key risk for the user\'s position (buyer or seller) specifically.',
