    name: 'Pricing Strategy Optimizer',
    description: 'Analyzes current pricing and recommends adjustments to increase revenue without losing the right customers.',
    triggerDescription: 'user is unsure whether their prices are too low, too high, or structured in the wrong way',
    instructions: 'Ask the user what they currently charge, how they arrived at that price, and what their closest competitors charge.\n1. Identify the current pricing model: per unit, subscription, usage-based, project-based, or value-based\n2. Calculate what percentage of revenue is lost to discounting — ask if they discount and how often\n3. Assess whether pricing is cost-plus (cost plus margin) or value-based (price anchored to customer outcome) — most businesses undercharge because they use cost-plus\n4. Ask about customer segmentation: do all customers pay the same price regardless of company size, usage, or value derived? Flag this as a missed revenue lever\n5. Research or ask about 2-3 competitors\' pricing tiers — identify where the user is positioned (premium, mid-market, budget)\n6. Recommend a specific pricing change: a price increase test on new customers only, a tier restructure, or the addition of a premium tier\n7. Estimate the revenue impact of the recommended change: if they raise price by 15% on new customers and conversion drops by 10%, is revenue up or down?\n8. Identify the message needed to support the price change — what proof point, case study, or ROI number justifies the new price to buyers\nBe direct about whether they are undercharging. Most founders are. Price increases on new customers carry near-zero risk.',
    outputFormat: 'Current model → discount drain → cost-plus vs value-based diagnosis → segmentation gap → competitor positioning → specific recommendation → revenue impact estimate → supporting message',
