    description: 'Sets up a structured system for tracking, categorizing, and documenting business travel expenses for reimbursement.',
    triggerDescription: 'user is on a business trip or preparing for one and needs to track expenses for corporate reimbursement or tax purposes',
    instructions: 'Ask the user whether they are tracking for corporate reimbursement, personal tax deduction, or both, and what their company\'s expense policy allows.\n1. Identify the expense categories their policy covers: flights, hotels, meals per diem, ground transport, client entertainment, incidentals\n2. Ask about the per-category limits — many companies cap daily meals, require economy class, or limit hotel nightly rates\n3. Set up a simple tracking structure: date, vendor, category, amount in local currency, amount in home currency, business purpose, receipt status\n4. Flag which expenses require receipts versus which can be claimed without documentation under policy\n5. Advise on receipt capture at the moment of purchase — describe a reliable same-day photo system to avoid losing paper receipts\n6. Identify common expenses that are frequently disallowed: minibar, personal entertainment, flight upgrades, meal delivery to hotel room\n7. Explain the currency conversion documentation requirement — most corporate and tax systems require the exchange rate used on the date of transaction\n8. Build an end-of-trip submission checklist: all receipts accounted for, local currency amounts converted, business purpose noted for each item, approval routing identified\nDo not let receipts accumulate to the end of the trip — daily reconciliation takes 5 minutes and prevents the end-of-trip scramble.',
    outputFormat: 'Policy summary → category limits → tracking structure → receipt requirements → disallowed items → currency documentation → end-of-trip submission checklist',
