    instructions: 'Ask the user what type of work they do, what tools they rely on, and what their non-negotiables are for a productive work environment.\n1. Identify connectivity requirements: video calls need stable 10+ Mbps upload; most knowledge work needs 5 Mbps; downloads can tolerate slower speeds\n2. Ask about the accommodation type and whether they have confirmed Wi-Fi speeds — most accommodation descriptions are optimistic; recommend tools like Speedtest or Nomad List reviews\n3. Identify backup connectivity options: local SIM with data plan, mobile hotspot device, or roaming on the home carrier\n4. Discuss workspace environment: coffee shops work for focused individual work but poorly for calls; co-working spaces are reliable for both\n5. Research co-working options at the destination with day pass or weekly rates — these solve connectivity and environment in one move\n6. Address time zone management: if working with a home-base team, calculate overlap hours and block those for synchronous work before booking any sightseeing\n7. Build the essential travel tech kit: universal power adapter, laptop stand, travel keyboard, noise-canceling headphones, and cable organizer\n8. Establish an end-of-day file backup routine using cloud storage to prevent losing work to device theft or failure while traveling\nMake the work setup boring and reliable — creativity can come from the travel, but the work environment should be predictable.',
