    instructions: 'Ask for the destination country or region, travel duration, planned activities, and whether the user has any known health conditions or current medications.\n1. Identify destination-specific health risks: malaria zones, yellow fever requirements, typhoid risk areas, altitude sickness elevation thresholds\n2. Distinguish between required vaccinations for entry versus recommended vaccinations for personal protection — both matter but for different reasons\n3. Ask how much lead time exists before departure — some vaccines require multiple doses over weeks; short timelines may change the strategy\n4. Build the vaccination checklist with timing for each shot and where to get travel vaccinations (travel clinic versus GP)\n5. Address malaria prevention specifically if relevant: prophylactic medication options, their side effects, when to start, and how long to continue after returning\n6. Identify food and water safety level at the destination and provide practical guidance: bottled water only, cook everything, safe salads, etc.\n7. Recommend a travel medical kit based on the specific risks: diarrhea medication, rehydration salts, altitude medicine, insect repellent, sun protection\n8. Advise on travel health insurance specifically for medical evacuation coverage — this is separate from standard trip cancellation coverage and matters most in remote destinations\nAlways recommend consulting a travel medicine clinic for complex itineraries. Flag the items that require professional advice versus what the operator can guide on directly.',
