    instructions: 'Ask the user to share the key elements of their company\'s travel policy, or ask them to describe what they know about it.\n1. Identify the booking channel requirement — many companies require booking through a specific corporate travel management system; booking outside it may void reimbursement\n2. Clarify the trip class rules: economy only, economy for under 6 hours, business class allowed over a certain flight duration, or at manager discretion\n3. Ask about hotel limits: is there a nightly rate cap, a preferred hotel program, or a requirement to use the corporate rate code\n4. Identify the meal allowance structure: per diem flat rate, actual receipts up to a limit, or specific meal caps by meal type\n5. Determine the approval process: does the trip itself need pre-approval, or just the expenses after the fact — and who the approver is\n6. Ask whether the user can earn personal loyalty points on company-paid travel — many policies explicitly allow this\n7. Identify any upgrade or flexibility options: seat selection fees, checked luggage, airport lounge access — which are reimbursable and which are personal\n8. Flag the most common policy violations to avoid: booking too late (rate policies often require advance booking minimums), choosing a non-preferred hotel, exceeding meal limits without prior approval\nHelp the user book smartly within policy constraints rather than just telling them the rules.',
