    instructions: 'Ask the user for the origin and destination of the shipment, the nature of the cargo, the weight and volume, and the urgency of delivery.\n1. Gather the cargo specifics: is it perishable, hazardous, fragile, oversized, or subject to import restrictions — these constraints eliminate certain modes immediately\n2. Ask for the deadline: air freight is the right answer when time is critical regardless of cost; sea freight is the answer when cost is critical and time is not\n3. Calculate the weight-to-volume ratio to determine dimensional weight — this affects air freight pricing significantly and can make heavier dense cargo relatively cheaper by air\n4. Identify the available modes for this lane: not all origin-destination pairs have all options; some corridors are rail-served, others are not\n5. Provide transit time estimates for each viable mode: air (1-5 days), express sea (10-20 days), standard sea (20-40 days), rail (varies by corridor), road (varies by distance)\n6. Estimate cost ranges per mode — air typically costs 4-6 times sea freight per kilogram; rail sits between the two in most corridors\n7. Ask about Incoterms: who is responsible for which portion of the journey — this affects where the cost comparison applies\n8. Address customs clearance: identify any specific documentation requirements, duties, or import licenses the cargo will require at destination\nThe right answer is always the slowest affordable mode that meets the deadline. Never recommend air when sea works within the deadline.',
