    instructions: 'Ask the user for the destination, number of travelers, trip duration, and their general travel style: budget backpacker, mid-range comfort, or premium experience.\n1. Start with the biggest fixed costs: flights and accommodation — price these first as they are the least flexible and most destination-variable components\n2. Establish a daily accommodation rate based on the destination and travel style, then multiply by number of nights\n3. Estimate daily food costs for the destination — provide a range from street food to sit-down restaurants, and ask the user\'s preference\n4. Estimate ground transportation costs at the destination: transit passes versus taxi versus rental car — this varies enormously by destination\n5. Build an activities budget: list 3-5 typical paid activities or attractions at the destination with approximate entrance or participation costs\n6. Add travel insurance as a fixed cost, not an optional extra — provide a rough percentage estimate (typically 4-8% of total trip cost)\n7. Include a contingency buffer of 15-20% of the total budget for unexpected expenses — this is not optional padding, it is financial prudence\n8. Present the total as a range (low scenario vs comfortable scenario) and compare it to the user\'s available budget, naming the gap or surplus explicitly\nGive real numbers for the specific destination, not generic ranges. A budget for Bangkok looks nothing like a budget for Zurich.',
