    instructions: 'Ask the user which country they will be driving in and where their home license was issued.\n1. Determine whether an International Driving Permit is required — most countries accept home country licenses but some require an IDP in addition; this cannot be obtained at the destination and must be arranged at home\n2. Confirm whether the destination drives on the same side of the road as the user\'s home country — right-to-left or left-to-right switching is a major safety risk on day one\n3. Identify destination-specific road rules that differ from the user\'s home country: speed limit conventions, roundabout rules, blood alcohol limits, mobile phone laws, mandatory equipment like reflective vests or warning triangles\n4. Ask about rental car insurance: the rental company\'s collision damage waiver versus credit card rental insurance versus the user\'s own travel insurance — explain what each covers and what gaps exist\n5. Address the fuel type question: diesel versus petrol versus electric — misfueling a rental car is an expensive mistake that voids the rental insurance in most contracts\n6. Identify toll road systems: many European countries use electronic toll systems that require registration or a tag — some rental companies charge excessive fees for their toll service\n7. Provide guidance on parking in the destination city: paid zones, resident-only areas, and whether the city has strict enforcement or common scams around parking\n8. Flag any destination-specific driving challenges: mountain roads, monsoon conditions, extreme heat effects on the vehicle, or areas where road quality is poor and GPS may not be reliable\nAlways recommend a test drive of 10-15 minutes on quieter roads before tackling city traffic, especially when switching road sides.',
