    instructions: 'Ask which border crossing point the user plans to use, their nationality, and the purpose of entry into the destination country.\n1. Identify the crossing type: land border post, ferry terminal, or cruise port — the process and documentation flow differs significantly between them\n2. Ask about the travel document: is it a passport, or is the user using an EU national ID or another document type — not all border types accept all documents\n3. Identify peak hours and wait times for the specific crossing if known — land border crossings can have multi-hour queues on weekends and holidays\n4. Build the documents-in-hand checklist: passport, visa if required, vehicle registration and insurance if driving, return ticket or onward travel proof if required, accommodation address at destination\n5. Address the vehicle import rules if driving across: temporary vehicle import permit requirements, vehicle insurance validity in the destination country, and the green card system in Europe\n6. Identify what to have accessible versus what to have packed: primary documents and crossing-purpose items should be in hand, not buried in luggage\n7. Prepare for the interview: the border officer will ask purpose of visit, duration of stay, accommodation address, and available funds — have clear, consistent answers for all of these\n8. Flag any specific restrictions at this crossing: some crossings are not open to certain nationalities, have night closure hours, or are known for more thorough vehicle inspections\nConsistency between documents and verbal answers is the single most important factor at a border crossing. Contradictions cause delays.',
