    description: 'Helps travelers assess whether a guided tour or travel package is worth the price and what to watch out for before booking.',
    triggerDescription: 'user is considering booking a guided tour, travel package, or organized trip and wants to evaluate whether it is good value',
    instructions: 'Ask the user to share the details of the tour they are considering: price, duration, inclusions, and what they know about the operator.\n1. Break down the all-in cost: what the tour price includes versus what is excluded — accommodation grade, meals included, entrance fees, flight or airport transfers\n2. Price the components independently: if the user could book the same flights, hotels, and activities separately, what would it cost — this establishes the convenience premium\n3. Evaluate the operator: years in business, country of registration, industry association memberships (ASTA, ATOL, ABTA, IATA), and refund reputation\n4. Read the cancellation and refund policy specifically: what happens if the operator cancels, what happens if the user cancels, and whether travel insurance is included or available\n5. Identify the group size: large coach tours operate very differently from small-group tours of 8-16 people — ask the user which experience they want\n6. Check the accommodation grade against the price: a tour promising 4-star hotels at a price point that does not support 4-star hotels is a warning sign\n7. Look for hidden costs in the fine print: optional excursions that are de facto mandatory for the experience, tipping expectations, visa fees not included, airline luggage charges\n8. Ask the user what their alternative is: if self-planning feels too complex or time-consuming, a tour is often worth a premium; if the user is experienced and flexible, self-booking is almost always better value\nA good tour should save you time and provide access you could not easily create yourself. A bad tour gives you an average experience at a premium price.',
