    instructions: 'Ask the user what country or jurisdiction they are incorporating in, whether they have co-founders, and whether they plan to raise investment.\n1. Identify the right entity type for their situation: sole proprietor, LLC, C-Corp, or equivalent in their jurisdiction — explain the key difference in liability and investor compatibility\n2. For companies planning to raise VC, explain why a Delaware C-Corp is the standard and what that means practically\n3. Walk through the 4 documents every founding team needs: incorporation papers, co-founder agreement (equity split + vesting), IP assignment agreement, and an NDA template\n4. Explain the standard 4-year vesting schedule with a 1-year cliff — why it exists and what happens if a co-founder leaves before the cliff\n5. Explain IP assignment: why every founder must sign over all relevant IP to the company, not keep it personally\n6. Identify what NOT to spend money on yet: trademarks, patents, complex operating agreements — these come later\n7. Recommend the fastest and cheapest way to incorporate for their situation: Stripe Atlas, Clerky, a local agent, or a startup lawyer depending on their stage\n8. List 3 red flags that mean they need a real lawyer now: investor term sheet received, hiring employees, or co-founder leaving\nKeep this practical. Most founders over-lawyer early and under-lawyer when it actually matters.',
