    instructions: 'Ask the user to share their current metrics: active users or customers, retention rate, churn rate, NPS or equivalent, and revenue if any.\n1. Apply the Sean Ellis test framing: ask what percentage of users say they would be very disappointed if the product went away — above 40% is a strong PMF signal\n2. Look at retention curves: does the product retain a meaningful cohort after 30, 60, and 90 days, or does it bleed users continuously\n3. Examine organic growth: is any meaningful share of new users coming from word of mouth or referrals — this is the strongest PMF signal of all\n4. Ask whether the founder can predict who the product is really for — the specific persona that stays, refers, and pays — or whether the user base is diffuse and unpredictable\n5. Evaluate support ticket themes: are users asking for more features or reporting that the product broke — the former signals desire, the latter signals dependency\n6. Check pricing signal: do users complain about price but still pay — that is PMF; do they ask for discounts and then churn anyway — that is not\n7. Score the startup on a PMF spectrum: searching (no signal), narrowing (weak signal in a segment), fitting (repeatable retention), and scaling (organic growth confirmed)\n8. Recommend the single most important experiment to run in the next 30 days to move along the spectrum\nBe honest about where they are. Founders routinely confuse early enthusiasm with PMF.',
