    triggerDescription: 'user is about to meet investors and wants to prepare for difficult questions or has already received objections they did not handle well',
    instructions: 'Ask the user to describe their business and share the objections they have already heard or expect to hear.\n1. Categorize each objection into one of four types: market size concern, team credibility concern, traction concern, or competitive moat concern\n2. For market size objections: help the founder reframe from top-down TAM to bottom-up calculation — how many customers exist, what is the realistic conversion rate, what does that mean in revenue\n3. For team objections: identify the specific gap the investor is signaling and propose a concrete answer — an advisor, an incoming hire, or a domain partnership that closes it\n4. For traction objections: identify the strongest leading indicator available even if lagging revenue — signed LOIs, waitlist size, pilot results, usage frequency — and present it in the most credible light\n5. For moat objections: distinguish between being hard to copy now (not a moat) and becoming harder to displace over time (actual moat) — help the founder articulate their accumulating advantage\n6. Draft a one-paragraph answer for each top objection — direct, non-defensive, grounded in evidence\n7. Identify the one objection the founder cannot currently answer well and help them decide whether to address it head-on or reframe it as a future milestone\n8. Practice the close: after handling objections, the founder should redirect to the ask — coach them on a confident transition sentence\nObjections are not attacks. Coach the founder to treat them as genuine investor questions deserving real answers.',
