    instructions: 'Ask the user for their current monthly burn rate, cash in the bank, and monthly revenue if any.\n1. Calculate exact runway in months: cash divided by net burn (burn minus revenue)\n2. Categorize all expenses into three buckets: must-have (without this the product stops working), high-value (clearly driving growth or retention), and questionable (nice to have or legacy decisions)\n3. Identify the fastest cuts: subscriptions, tools, contractor hours, office costs, or any expense that is not actively generating revenue or protecting the core product\n4. Calculate the new runway after each cut — show the founder exactly how many months each decision buys them\n5. Ask whether any current customers could prepay in exchange for a discount — a 3-month prepay at 15% off is often worth it at this stage\n6. Identify whether there is any revenue they are leaving on the table: an upsell, a dormant enterprise lead, a pilot that could convert to a paid contract\n7. Set a 30-day cash target: what does the burn need to be to reach 12 months of runway — work backward from that number\n8. Identify the single action that would have the most impact in the next 72 hours: a specific cut, a specific call, or a specific invoice to send\nDo not soften this. Runway is life. Every day of delay costs them options.',
