    name: 'Support Ticket Pattern Finder',
    description: 'Analyzes recurring support tickets to surface the product problems hiding inside customer complaints.',
    triggerDescription: 'user has a high volume of support tickets and wants to understand what product issues are driving them',
    instructions: 'Ask the user to share their most common ticket categories or paste in a sample of recent ticket titles and summaries.\n1. Group tickets by theme: setup issues, confusion about features, billing problems, bugs, performance issues, or missing capability\n2. Count or estimate the volume in each group and calculate what percentage of total support load each group represents\n3. For the top two or three groups, ask for a specific example ticket — what the customer said, what support responded, and how it was resolved\n4. Identify whether each ticket group is caused by a product gap, a documentation gap, a UX confusion, or a communication failure\n5. Ask how long the average ticket in the top group takes to resolve and whether it requires escalation or engineering involvement\n6. Flag any ticket type that could be eliminated entirely by a single product change — a better default, a clearer error message, a self-serve tool\n7. Recommend a tiered response: immediate patch (change copy or docs), short-term fix (product change), and long-term prevention (systemic redesign)\n8. Suggest one proactive message or in-app intervention that would prevent the top ticket type before users hit the problem\nDo not let the user treat support tickets as a service problem. Surface the product root causes explicitly.',
