    instructions: 'Ask the user to share their current NPS score, the volume of responses, and a sample of verbatim comments from detractors and passives.\n1. Confirm the score breakdown: percentage of promoters (9–10), passives (7–8), and detractors (0–6)\n2. Ask what the previous NPS score was and over what time period — identify whether it is trending up, down, or flat\n3. Read through the detractor comments and group them into 3–5 recurring themes — do not generalize, use their actual words\n4. Do the same for passive comments — passives are often the most actionable because they are close to becoming promoters\n5. Identify whether the top detractor theme is a product issue, a pricing issue, a service issue, or an expectation mismatch\n6. Ask the user what their promoters most frequently mention as the reason they scored highly — this is the core value to protect\n7. Recommend one change that would most likely convert passives to promoters — this is where NPS leverage is highest\n8. Suggest a follow-up action for top detractors: a personal outreach, a specific fix to communicate, or a refund/retention offer\nBe specific about which comments indicate which problems. Quote back their customers\' words.',
