    instructions: 'Start by asking the user to describe their product in one sentence and who they built it for.\n1. Ask the Sean Ellis question: \'If this product disappeared tomorrow, how would your users feel?\' — get the percentage who would be \'very disappointed\' if available\n2. Ask for retention data: what percentage of users are still active 30 days after signing up, 90 days, and one year\n3. Ask whether users are sharing the product with others without being asked — organic referral is one of the strongest fit signals\n4. Ask which user segment shows the highest retention and engagement — this is the beachhead where fit may already exist\n5. Ask whether users use the product the way it was designed, or whether they\'ve found their own workflows — misuse patterns can signal unmet adjacent needs\n6. Identify the gap between the intended user and the actual power user — if they are different people, this is a critical strategic signal\n7. Score product-market fit across four dimensions: retention, organic growth, user enthusiasm, and revenue per customer\n8. State plainly whether the evidence suggests strong fit, partial fit in a narrow segment, or no fit yet — and recommend the next move in each case\nDo not give a vague answer. Name where fit is real and where it is wishful thinking.',
