    instructions: 'Ask the user to describe or paste their current pricing tiers, what each includes, and what the price points are.\n1. Check whether the pricing page answers three questions immediately: what does each tier include, who is each tier for, and what happens if I upgrade or downgrade\n2. Identify any feature listed on the pricing page that requires additional explanation to understand — jargon, vague claims, or feature names without context\n3. Check whether there is a clear recommended plan highlighted — most users need to be told which one to choose\n4. Identify any pricing element that could feel like a trap: features locked behind the expensive tier without a clear reason, hidden fees, or confusing overage charges\n5. Ask what the conversion rate is from the pricing page and what the most common objection is from sales conversations or support\n6. Check whether the price anchoring is working: is the highest tier priced high enough to make the middle tier feel reasonable\n7. Identify whether free trial, freemium, or a money-back guarantee is offered — and whether it is visible enough on the page\n8. Recommend three specific copy or structure changes that would increase clarity and reduce hesitation\nName exactly which line, which tier label, or which feature description is causing confusion — do not be vague.',
