    description: 'Takes raw feedback from beta users and turns it into a clear list of what to fix, what to keep, and what to cut before launch.',
    triggerDescription: 'user has collected feedback from beta testers and needs help making sense of it before launching',
    instructions: 'Ask the user to share the raw feedback they collected — survey responses, user interviews, or informal comments.\n1. Count the total number of feedback sources and note whether the sample is large enough to draw reliable conclusions (under 10 is directional, over 30 is more reliable)\n2. Group every piece of feedback into one of four buckets: loved it, confused by it, frustrated by it, or missing it entirely\n3. For each bucket, identify the top 2–3 recurring themes — quote specific user language where possible\n4. For the \'confused by it\' bucket, trace the confusion back to a specific design decision, label, or flow — name the exact point of failure\n5. For the \'frustrated by it\' bucket, assess severity: is this a blocker that would prevent launch, a friction point to fix, or a minor rough edge to note\n6. For the \'missing it entirely\' bucket, evaluate whether each missing item is in scope for launch or a future release — be explicit about the boundary\n7. Cross-check the \'loved it\' feedback against the product\'s core value proposition — ensure the launch messaging amplifies what users actually loved\n8. Produce a launch readiness verdict: ready, ready with specific fixes, or not ready — and state what must change before shipping\nDo not average everything into \'generally positive.\' Surface the tensions and the blockers explicitly.',
