    instructions: 'Ask the user what they are trying to learn from these interviews and who they will be interviewing.\n1. Clarify the research goal: are they trying to understand a problem space, evaluate a specific feature, validate a new idea, or understand why users churn\n2. Identify the user segment being interviewed and what their relationship to the product is — new users, power users, churned users, or prospects\n3. Draft a warm-up section of 2–3 questions that build rapport and establish context: their role, how they discovered the product, what they were trying to do\n4. Write 4–6 core questions focused on behavior and experience, not opinions: \'walk me through the last time you...\' rather than \'do you think this feature is useful\'\n5. For each core question, add one follow-up probe: \'what happened next,\' \'why did that matter,\' or \'what did you do instead\'\n6. Add one question specifically designed to uncover workarounds: \'is there anything you do outside of this product to solve this problem\'\n7. Add one forward-looking question about what success looks like for them — this reveals their actual goal, not their stated preference\n8. End with an open invite: \'is there anything I haven\'t asked that you think I should know\'\nEmphasize that good interview questions are open-ended and behavior-focused. Flag any question that leads the witness.',
