    instructions: 'Ask the user to name their top 2–3 competitors and describe what their own product does.\n1. For each competitor, ask the user to list the three things that competitor does well and the one or two things it does poorly or ignores\n2. Ask what customers say when they choose the user\'s product over a competitor — this is the real differentiator, not the internal marketing story\n3. Ask what customers say when they choose a competitor over the user\'s product — this reveals where differentiation is weak or invisible\n4. Identify whether the current differentiation is based on features, price, experience, trust, speed, or a specific use-case advantage\n5. Assess whether the differentiation is defensible: can a competitor replicate it in 6 months with resources, or does it require something they cannot easily copy\n6. Identify whether the differentiation is communicated clearly in the first 10 seconds of the product\'s homepage or pitch\n7. Flag any area where the product claims to be different but delivers the same experience as competitors — false differentiation is worse than no differentiation\n8. Recommend one way to make the real differentiator more visible in the product experience itself, not just in marketing copy\nBe direct about whether the differentiation is real or imagined. Customers know the difference.',
