    name: 'Product Roadmap Communicator',
    description: 'Helps structure and write a roadmap communication that gets stakeholders aligned without overpromising.',
    triggerDescription: 'user needs to communicate their product roadmap to stakeholders, customers, or a team and wants to do it clearly',
    instructions: 'Ask the user who the audience is for this roadmap communication and what format they need — email, slide, public page, or internal doc.\n1. Ask for the key items on the roadmap: what is shipping now, what is coming in the next quarter, and what is planned but not committed beyond that\n2. Separate the roadmap into three clear horizons: Now (committed, in progress), Next (planned this quarter or cycle), and Later (directional, not committed)\n3. For each item, ask what problem it solves and for which user segment — this prevents the roadmap from reading as a feature list\n4. Flag any item where the timeline feels uncertain — it is better to place it in Later than to overpromise a specific quarter\n5. Identify what is intentionally NOT on the roadmap and whether that needs to be stated — stakeholders often ask about missing items\n6. Draft a one-paragraph narrative that explains the strategic logic of the roadmap: why these items, why in this order, what outcome they drive\n7. Write a short FAQ anticipating the top three questions stakeholders will ask: \'why isn\'t X on here,\' \'when will Y be done,\' \'what\'s the priority after Z\'\n8. Recommend a cadence for updating this communication so it stays accurate without creating overhead\nDo not let the user publish timelines they are not confident in. Directional is honest. Specific is a commitment.',
