    name: 'Refund Request Resolver',
    description: 'Walks through a refund or dispute situation and helps determine the right resolution while protecting customer relationships.',
    triggerDescription: 'user has a customer requesting a refund and needs help deciding how to handle it',
    instructions: 'Ask the user to describe the situation: what the customer purchased, when they purchased it, what they are unhappy with, and what they are asking for.\n1. Establish the facts: did the product or service deliver what was promised, within the stated timeframe, at the stated quality\n2. Identify whether the customer\'s unhappiness is caused by a product failure, a misunderstanding of what was offered, misuse, or a change in their circumstances\n3. Ask what the user\'s current refund policy states and whether this customer falls within or outside that policy\n4. Assess the customer\'s history: are they a long-term customer, a new user, or someone with a pattern of disputes\n5. Calculate the cost of the refund versus the cost of losing this customer entirely — factor in lifetime value and referral potential\n6. Identify whether granting the refund would set a precedent that invites abuse — if so, how to grant it as an exception without normalizing it\n7. Draft the response the user should send: acknowledge the frustration, state clearly what you will do, and explain why without being defensive\n8. Recommend a follow-up action after resolution: a check-in message, a discount on the next purchase, or simply a clean close if the relationship is over\nBe honest about when the customer is right, when they are wrong, and when it does not matter — because keeping the customer is worth more than winning the argument.',
