    description: 'Writes a structured demo script that shows the product\'s value in the customer\'s own terms rather than a feature tour.',
    triggerDescription: 'user needs to demo their product to a potential customer or audience and wants a script that converts',
    instructions: 'Ask the user who they are demoing to, what the prospect\'s main problem is, and what outcome they are hoping the product will deliver.\n1. Start the script with the problem statement in the prospect\'s language — mirror what they said in the discovery call or inquiry, not what the product marketing says\n2. Structure the demo around three moments of value, not three features — each moment should answer \'here is how your life gets better\'\n3. For each moment of value, identify the exact screen, flow, or action to show — do not describe it vaguely, name the specific click path\n4. Script the narration for each moment: what to say before showing it (set up the problem), during (narrate what is happening and why it matters), and after (land the value)\n5. Add one \'wow moment\' in the middle of the demo — a result, a time saved, or a comparison that makes the prospect feel something\n6. Anticipate the top two objections and insert handling naturally into the demo flow rather than saving them for the end\n7. Write the closing ask: what you want the prospect to do next — a trial, a follow-up call, a decision — and make it specific\n8. Add a fallback script for if the demo goes off-track: how to recover from a technical failure, a wrong question, or a distracted audience\nDo not let the demo become a feature tour. Every screen should be there because it answers a prospect question.',
