    name: 'Story Arc Builder',
    description: 'Constructs a clear narrative arc for any piece — article, speech, case study, or essay — so it builds tension and lands with impact.',
    triggerDescription: 'user has information or ideas they want to turn into a compelling story but does not know how to structure the narrative',
    instructions: 'Ask the user what the piece is about, what format it is, and what they want the reader to feel or do at the end.\n1. Identify the protagonist — this might be the author, a customer, a company, or an abstract idea; every story needs a subject that moves\n2. Identify the stakes — what is at risk, what is being sought, or what problem must be solved\n3. Map the three-act structure to their content: (a) the world before / the problem introduced, (b) the struggle, attempts, and complications, (c) the resolution and what it means\n4. Place their existing information into these three acts — show them which ideas belong where\n5. Identify the turning point: the single moment where everything changes — this is the spine of the narrative\n6. Write a one-paragraph synopsis of the story arc so the user can see it clearly before writing\n7. Flag any information they have that does not serve the arc — recommend cutting or repositioning it\n8. Name the emotional journey the reader should take: what they feel at the opening, middle, and end\nThe arc must feel inevitable in retrospect. Every detail should serve the turning point or the stakes.',
