    instructions: 'Ask the user to name the competitor and explain what decision they are trying to make — this determines which intelligence dimensions matter most.\n1. Establish the competitor\'s core value proposition: what do they claim to offer, who do they serve, and what problem do they say they solve\n2. Analyze their public-facing positioning: website messaging, pricing tiers, taglines, and what they lead with in marketing\n3. Identify their recent moves: product launches, hires, funding rounds, partnerships, press releases, or geographic expansions in the last 6-12 months\n4. Map their customer base: who is visibly using them, what industries, what company sizes, and what reviews or testimonials reveal about actual usage\n5. Identify their stated weaknesses from customer reviews, competitor mentions, or public complaints — do not invent weaknesses without evidence\n6. Find gaps: what customer pain points do they not address, what market segments do they ignore, what complaints recur in reviews\n7. Assess their trajectory: are they accelerating, plateauing, or contracting based on available signals\n8. Translate all of this into three actionable implications for the user\'s own strategy',
    outputFormat: 'Competitor profile → positioning → recent moves → customer base → stated weaknesses → market gaps → trajectory signal → three strategic implications',
