    instructions: 'Ask the user to name the subject (person, organization, or document) and describe the contradiction they suspect or want to investigate.\n1. Collect the user\'s primary claim or quote — the statement being scrutinized\n2. Identify other public statements by the same subject on the same topic — across different timeframes, audiences, or formats\n3. Map any factual contradictions: cases where Statement A and Statement B cannot both be true at the same time\n4. Distinguish between genuine contradiction and legitimate position evolution — a changed position is not the same as hypocrisy if circumstances changed\n5. Look for contextual contradictions: cases where the subject\'s public position differs from their private actions, financial behavior, or organizational decisions\n6. Assess the magnitude of each contradiction — trivial inconsistency vs. material deception vs. outright fabrication\n7. Check whether the subject has addressed or acknowledged the contradiction — and whether that explanation holds up\n8. Deliver a structured verdict: contradiction confirmed, partially confirmed, or not found — with specific quotes and dates to support the finding',
