    triggerDescription: 'user wants to understand whether a news article, report, or piece of content is presenting information objectively or steering them toward a conclusion',
    instructions: 'Ask the user to share the specific content they want analyzed — an article, report, statement, or broadcast summary.\n1. Identify the dominant framing: what is the central story being told, and what worldview does it assume the reader holds\n2. Analyze word choices: flag loaded language, emotionally charged words, or terms that imply a verdict rather than describe a fact\n3. Check the sources cited: who is quoted, who is absent, and whether the voices included represent the range of credible perspectives on this topic\n4. Identify what is omitted: what facts, context, or counterarguments would complicate the narrative and have been left out\n5. Examine the headline vs. the body: does the headline accurately represent the evidence in the article, or does it overclaim\n6. Look at sequencing: stories that lead with emotionally charged elements before facts prime the reader\'s interpretation — flag this pattern\n7. Identify the publication or author\'s known position, funding, or track record of bias in previous coverage\n8. Deliver an objectivity assessment: balanced, leaning with transparency, slanted, or propaganda — with specific examples from the text to support the rating',
