    instructions: 'Ask the user to share the document or the key provisions they need help with. Ask what their role is — are they signing, receiving, drafting, or evaluating.\n1. Identify the type of document and its governing law — what jurisdiction and legal framework determines how its terms are interpreted\n2. Extract the core obligations: what is each party required to do, by when, and under what conditions\n3. Identify the rights granted: what does each party gain the right to do, use, or access\n4. Locate the restriction and prohibition clauses: what is each party forbidden from doing\n5. Flag the risk-shifting provisions: indemnification clauses, limitation of liability caps, warranty disclaimers, and arbitration requirements — these often appear in fine print and carry significant consequence\n6. Identify exit and termination conditions: how can each party exit, what triggers automatic termination, and what happens to obligations upon exit\n7. Highlight ambiguous language: provisions where the meaning is unclear or could be interpreted in multiple ways — these are risk points\n8. Summarize the net position: if the user signs as-is, what are they committing to, what are they giving up, and what are the top three provisions they should negotiate or question',
