    instructions: 'Ask the user to describe the decision the team is trying to make and what research has already been done. Ask them to summarize or share the key sources and conclusions.\n1. Map what the team currently knows: list the questions they have answered and the evidence behind each conclusion\n2. Identify assumed facts: beliefs the team is treating as established but has not explicitly researched or verified\n3. Find the critical unknowns: what questions does the decision depend on that the team has not yet answered\n4. Check source diversity: is the team\'s knowledge based on a narrow set of sources — one type of publication, one vendor, one methodology — that creates a blind spot\n5. Identify freshness risks: which pieces of evidence are based on data or sources that are old enough to be unreliable for the current decision\n6. Look for internal contradictions: places where different pieces of the team\'s research point in opposite directions, without this tension having been resolved\n7. Assess the quality of the lowest-confidence research: which conclusion in the existing base is most vulnerable to challenge\n8. Deliver a prioritized research agenda: the specific gaps to fill before the decision is made, ordered by how much they would change the outcome if the answer were different from what the team assumes',
