    instructions: 'Ask the user to state the specific claim they want to verify and what level of confidence they need before acting.\n1. State the claim precisely: vague claims cannot be triangulated — narrow the assertion to something concrete and falsifiable\n2. Identify the first source: the closest to the original or most authoritative — a primary document, official record, or direct witness\n3. Identify a second source that is structurally independent of the first: different institution, different methodology, different funding, different time period\n4. Identify a third source that provides a different type of evidence: if the first two are documentary, the third should be testimonial, observational, or data-based\n5. Check whether the three sources genuinely conflict or converge: if they all ultimately trace back to the same original source, triangulation has failed\n6. Assess the incentive alignment: do any of these sources have a reason to report this claim regardless of whether it is true — shared motive undermines triangulation\n7. Identify what evidence would disprove this claim, and check whether that evidence has been sought and not found, or simply not sought at all\n8. Determine the confidence level: if three independent sources with different incentives confirm the same specific claim, state it as established. If two confirm and one is neutral, state it as probable. If sources conflict, state it as contested.',
