    instructions: 'Ask the user to describe the situation and name the stakeholders they already know about. Ask what decision or outcome they are working toward.\n1. Generate a complete stakeholder list: expand beyond the obvious parties to include indirect stakeholders, regulators, media, public interest groups, and anyone whose behavior could affect the outcome\n2. For each stakeholder, identify their formal position (what they say they want) and their underlying interest (what they actually need)\n3. Assess each stakeholder\'s power: their ability to block, accelerate, or shape the outcome — distinguish formal authority from informal influence\n4. Identify each stakeholder\'s BATNA (best alternative to a negotiated agreement): what will they do if they cannot get what they want from this situation\n5. Map the stakeholder relationships: who is aligned with whom, who is in conflict with whom, and who influences whom\n6. Identify the swing stakeholders: those whose position is not fixed and whose movement could determine the outcome\n7. Assess timing: which stakeholders become more or less influential at different phases of the process\n8. Develop an engagement strategy: which stakeholders should be approached first, in what order, and with what argument or offer to move them toward the desired outcome',
