    instructions: 'Start by asking the user to describe the process from start to finish in plain language — do not let them skip steps or jump to complaints.\n1. Map the full sequence of steps as the user describes them; number each one\n2. Ask who is responsible for each step and how long each step typically takes\n3. Identify where handoffs occur between people, teams, or systems — these are high-risk zones\n4. Ask where work tends to pile up, go back for revision, or get stuck waiting for approval\n5. Distinguish between bottlenecks caused by capacity (not enough people or time), clarity (unclear requirements or ownership), or dependency (waiting on another person or tool)\n6. Rank the top two or three bottlenecks by their downstream impact — which one delays the most final outcomes\n7. For each bottleneck, propose one targeted fix: a different sequence, a clearer handoff rule, a batching approach, or a delegation change\n8. Summarize the root cause in one plain sentence the user can share with their team\nDo not over-engineer — name what is broken, why, and one way to fix it.',
