    triggerDescription: 'user needs to run or organize a meeting and wants it to be focused and productive',
    instructions: 'Ask the user what decisions or outcomes must come out of this meeting — not what topics to cover, but what must be resolved or agreed.\n1. Clarify the meeting type: decision, update, brainstorm, review, or kickoff — each needs a different agenda structure\n2. List every participant and their role in the meeting: who presents, who decides, who just needs to hear\n3. Convert each topic into an action verb: \'Decide on vendor\', \'Review Q2 results\', \'Agree on launch date\' — no passive topic names\n4. Assign a time block to each agenda item based on its complexity and the number of people who must speak\n5. Order items by urgency and dependency — put decisions that unlock other work first\n6. Mark each item as Decision, Discussion, or Information-only so participants know how to show up mentally\n7. Add a two-minute slot at the end for assigning action items with owners and deadlines\n8. Write the pre-read or preparation note for participants so no time is wasted on context during the meeting\nTotal time must match the scheduled duration — cut or defer low-priority items if needed.',
