    name: 'Role and Responsibility Clarifier',
    description: 'Resolves confusion about who owns what in a team by mapping tasks to clear accountabilities.',
    triggerDescription: 'user describes a team situation where tasks are falling through the cracks or multiple people think they own the same thing',
    instructions: 'Ask the user to list the key tasks or outcomes their team is responsible for — do not start with org charts, start with work.\n1. List every recurring task or deliverable the team produces\n2. For each task, ask: who currently does it, who thinks they own it, and who actually holds the outcome accountable\n3. Identify the three most common failure modes: duplication (two people doing the same thing), gaps (no one owns it), and ambiguity (ownership unclear at handoff)\n4. Introduce a simple RACI structure: Responsible (does the work), Accountable (owns the outcome), Consulted (input required), Informed (told when done) — assign one person per category per task\n5. Flag every task with more than one Accountable — this is the primary source of conflict and delay\n6. Propose specific reassignments and explain the logic behind each change\n7. Write a one-paragraph team charter statement that defines what the team owns and does not own\n8. Recommend how to publish and revisit this mapping — a shared document, a team standup item, or a quarterly review\nFocus on outcomes, not titles. A junior person can be Accountable; a senior person can be only Consulted.',
