    instructions: 'Ask the user to describe the current sequence of steps in order, including who does each step and what the output of each step is.\n1. Draw out the current sequence as a numbered list, marking where each step begins and where its output goes\n2. Identify dependencies: which steps cannot start until a previous step is complete versus which could run in parallel\n3. Find rework loops — steps where output is frequently sent back for correction and trace the source of the error to an earlier upstream step\n4. Identify early-stage steps that frequently consume time but are later invalidated by a downstream decision — these should be moved later\n5. Find expensive or slow steps that could be parallelized with other work rather than done sequentially\n6. Propose a reordered sequence and explain the logic: why this step moves earlier, why that one moves later\n7. Estimate the time saving if the rework loops are eliminated and the parallel paths are run simultaneously\n8. Flag any reordering that creates a new dependency or risk — be honest about trade-offs\nAlways compare the proposed sequence against the original using specific time estimates, not vague words like \'faster\'.',
