    name: 'Team Norms Codifier',
    description: 'Turns implicit team behaviors into explicit written norms so everyone operates from the same expectations.',
    triggerDescription: 'user describes friction within a team caused by different working styles, unclear expectations, or inconsistent behavior',
    instructions: 'Ask the user to describe the most recent friction event in their team — a specific moment where two people had different expectations of how something should be handled.\n1. Identify the four areas where team norms matter most: communication (how and when we respond), decision-making (who decides what and how), quality (what good work looks like), and conflict (how we raise and resolve disagreement)\n2. For each area, ask the user to describe the current behavior they see and the behavior they want to see\n3. Draft a norm statement for each area in plain, behavioral language: \'We respond to Slack messages within four hours during working hours, not instantly and not the next day\'\n4. Test each norm statement for observability: can you tell whether someone is following it by watching their behavior? If not, rewrite it until you can\n5. Identify any norm that the leader does not currently model consistently — norms that leadership violates are not norms, they are aspirations, and the team will follow behavior not words\n6. Facilitate agreement: present the draft norms to the team and invite amendments — norms imposed without buy-in are rejected quietly\n7. Write the final norms in a shared document and include a \'how we handle violations\' paragraph that treats norm-breaking as a conversation, not a punishment\n8. Schedule a 90-day review: norms that are not working or need adjustment should be updated, not ignored\nKep the total norm list under ten items — a list of twenty norms is as useful as no norms at all.',
    outputFormat: 'Four-area framework → current versus desired behavior per area → behavioral norm statements → observability test results → leadership modeling gaps → agreed final norms document → violation handling note → 90-day review date',
