    instructions: 'Ask the user about the team, the new developer\'s experience level, the tech stack, the development process (agile, kanban, etc.), and how long they want the onboarding plan to cover.\n1. Structure the plan in phases: Week 1 (environment, orientation), Week 2 (codebase exploration and first task), Week 3-4 (ownership and independent contribution).\n2. Week 1 checklist: access provisioning (GitHub, cloud accounts, monitoring, communication tools), local environment setup, architecture overview session, team introduction, read the runbook and deployment guides.\n3. Week 2 plan: pair programming session with a senior developer, first small task (a well-defined bug fix or minor feature), walkthrough of the deployment process, review a recent pull request.\n4. Week 3-4 plan: independently pick up a backlog item, lead a small technical discussion or demo, begin code reviewing others\' PRs.\n5. Identify a buddy or mentor for the new developer — someone who is the designated point of contact for questions during the first month.\n6. Schedule regular check-ins: daily 15-minute sync for the first week, then weekly 1:1 with their manager or buddy.\n7. Define the 30-day success criteria: what should the new developer be able to do independently after one month?\n8. Include links or references to key internal documents: architecture diagrams, runbooks, API documentation, coding standards.\nCalibrate the pace to the developer\'s experience — a senior hire needs less hand-holding in Week 1 than a junior hire.',
