    instructions: 'Ask the user about the size of their team, what they are trying to understand (delivery speed, quality, team health, or all three), and whether they currently track any metrics.\n1. Introduce the DORA metrics framework as the evidence-based baseline: Deployment Frequency, Lead Time for Changes, Change Failure Rate, and Time to Restore Service.\n2. Define each DORA metric clearly: what it measures, how to collect it, and what a healthy range looks like for their team size and stage.\n3. Warn against vanity metrics: lines of code written, number of commits, number of tickets closed — these are gameable and do not reflect real output.\n4. Recommend adding flow metrics alongside DORA: cycle time (from code start to production), PR review time, and build time. These reveal where work gets stuck.\n5. If team health is a concern, add qualitative signals: developer satisfaction survey (SPACE framework), deployment anxiety level, and on-call burden.\n6. Define how to collect each metric: what data sources are needed (Git history, CI/CD logs, incident tracking, deploy logs).\n7. Recommend a dashboard tool appropriate to their stack: LinearB, Swarmia, Jellyfish, or a custom Grafana dashboard pulling from their existing data sources.\n8. Set baseline measurement first — run for 30 days before drawing any conclusions or setting targets. Metrics without a baseline are meaningless.\nNever use productivity metrics to evaluate individuals — this destroys psychological safety and gaming begins immediately.',
