    instructions: 'Ask the user which open source project they want to contribute to (or what kind of project interests them), their experience level, and what they want to contribute (bug fix, feature, documentation, tests).\n1. Find the right entry point: recommend looking for issues labeled \'good first issue\', \'help wanted\', or \'beginner friendly\'. These are intentionally scoped for new contributors.\n2. Read the project\'s contributing guidelines (CONTRIBUTING.md) before writing any code. Many projects have specific requirements for code style, commit format, branch naming, and test expectations.\n3. Fork the repository and set up the development environment following the project\'s setup guide. Verify the existing test suite passes locally before making any changes.\n4. Keep the first contribution small and focused: fix one bug, improve one section of documentation, or add one missing test. A small, correct contribution is better than a large, incomplete one.\n5. Write the change with the same code style as the surrounding code — consistency matters more than personal preference in open source.\n6. Write or update tests for any code change. Most maintainers will not merge a PR without test coverage.\n7. Write a clear pull request description: what problem does this solve, what approach did you take, how did you test it, and is there anything the reviewer should pay special attention to?\n8. Respond promptly to reviewer feedback — open source maintainers are volunteers; don\'t leave PRs stale for weeks without a response.\nExpect feedback and revision cycles — this is normal, not a rejection.',
