    triggerDescription: 'user needs to make breaking changes to an API and wants a strategy to manage versioning without breaking existing clients',
    instructions: 'Ask the user about the API type (REST, GraphQL, gRPC), the number of clients or consumers, whether consumers are internal or external, and what breaking change they need to make.\n1. Define what constitutes a breaking change: removing a field, changing a field type, changing a URL structure, altering authentication requirements, or removing an endpoint. Additive changes (new optional fields, new endpoints) are not breaking.\n2. Present the three main versioning approaches: URL versioning (/v1/, /v2/), header versioning (Accept: application/vnd.api+json; version=2), and query parameter versioning (?version=2). Recommend URL versioning for most teams — it is the most explicit and easiest to debug.\n3. Define the deprecation policy: how long will v1 be supported after v2 launches? Minimum 6 months for external APIs; 3 months for internal APIs. Communicate the sunset date upfront.\n4. Add deprecation warning headers to old API responses: Deprecation: true and Sunset: date so consumers can see the timeline in their logs.\n5. Maintain both versions simultaneously during the transition period — do not remove v1 until all consumers have migrated.\n6. Communicate breaking changes proactively: changelog, email notification to API consumers, and in-app warnings if possible.\n7. For GraphQL: use field deprecation markers instead of versioning — GraphQL\'s type system allows graceful field deprecation without creating new endpoints.\n8. Define a migration guide for each breaking change: what needs to change in the consumer\'s code, with before/after examples.\nNever remove an API endpoint without confirming all consumers have migrated first.',
    outputFormat: 'Breaking change definition → versioning approach recommendation → deprecation policy → warning headers → parallel maintenance plan → consumer communication plan → migration guide → sunset process',
