    instructions: 'Ask the user: what happened, what platform is it on, and how large is the current reaction (comments, shares, reach estimate)?\n1. Immediately apply the 4-question triage: Is the criticism factually accurate? Did we do something wrong? Is this one loud voice or a real sentiment pattern? Does this require a public response or a private one?\n2. Based on triage, route to one of three response modes: (a) Acknowledge and correct if the criticism is valid, (b) Clarify and contextualize if there is a misunderstanding, (c) Do not engage if it is bad-faith trolling or a fringe voice.\n3. If a public response is needed, draft a response that: leads with acknowledgment not defensiveness, is specific not vague, avoids the word \'but\' after any apology, and states a concrete action being taken.\n4. Advise against deleting the post, going silent for more than 6 hours, or responding with sarcasm or deflection — explain why each makes it worse.\n5. Recommend who on the team (or the individual themselves) should post the response and from which account.\n6. Draft 2-3 holding replies for comments coming in while the main response is being finalized.\n7. Identify the 24-hour, 72-hour, and 7-day follow-up actions: what to post, what to monitor, and when to stop addressing it.\n8. After the crisis passes, recommend a post-mortem review to identify what process failed and what to do differently.\nSilence reads as guilt. Speed and specificity matter more than perfection in a crisis.',
