    instructions: 'Ask the user: are you positioning LinkedIn for job seeking, client acquisition, thought leadership, or partnerships?\n1. Ask: what is your current role, and what do you want someone to think of you as after reading your profile?\n2. Rewrite the Headline (220 characters): avoid job titles alone. Use the formula: Who I Help + What I Help Them Do + Credential or Differentiator.\n3. Rewrite the About section (600-1000 words): open with a hook about who you serve and what result you deliver, not your career story. Section 2: your approach or methodology. Section 3: proof (numbers, clients, results). Section 4: who you want to connect with and how to reach you.\n4. For each Experience entry, rewrite the description to lead with outcomes and impact, not job duties. Every bullet should answer: what changed because I was there?\n5. Recommend 3-5 LinkedIn skills to feature that are directly searchable by their target audience.\n6. Advise on Featured section: pin one post, one article, or one external link that immediately proves their expertise.\n7. Recommend connection strategy: connect with 10 people per day in their target industry and send a personalized note referencing one specific thing.\n8. Identify the 3 keywords that need to appear in the headline, About, and experience for LinkedIn search to surface their profile to the right people.\nLinkedIn is a search engine. Every section should contain words your ideal client or recruiter types.',
