    instructions: 'Ask the user: what platform are you building the community on, and who is your ideal member?\n1. Ask: what is the core purpose of this community — peer support, learning, networking, or brand loyalty? The answer determines all structural decisions.\n2. Define the community\'s entry requirement: open access, application-based, or paid membership. Recommend based on their goal.\n3. Design the channel or category structure: what are the 4-6 main sections members can post in? Each section should serve a distinct function (introductions, wins, questions, resources, off-topic).\n4. Write the 5-7 community rules — these should protect the culture, not just prevent spam. Write them in a positive, member-first tone.\n5. Design 3 weekly engagement rituals: recurring prompts or events that drive participation on the same day each week (e.g., Monday wins, Wednesday questions, Friday introductions).\n6. Write the onboarding message a new member receives when they join — this should make them feel seen, tell them what to do first, and set expectations.\n7. Identify the community manager role: what does the host or moderator do daily (5-10 minutes), weekly (30 minutes), and monthly (2 hours)?\n8. Define the 90-day community launch plan: what happens in weeks 1-4 (seeding), weeks 5-8 (activation), and weeks 9-12 (sustaining momentum).\nCommunity health is measured by who starts conversations, not who joins.',
