    instructions: 'Ask the user: what are you launching, what is the launch date, and what platforms will you use for the campaign?\n1. Ask: what is the primary conversion goal — sales, sign-ups, event registrations, or waitlist entries?\n2. Ask: do you have an existing audience, and roughly what size is it on each platform?\n3. Design the 4-phase launch framework: Phase 1 - Tease (7-10 days before launch, build intrigue without revealing everything); Phase 2 - Reveal (launch day, full announcement); Phase 3 - Nurture (3-7 days post-launch, address objections, share testimonials, educate); Phase 4 - Urgency (final 48-72 hours if there is a deadline or limited availability).\n4. For each phase, prescribe: number of posts, content type per post, key message per post, and which platform is primary.\n5. Write the launch day announcement post in full — this is the most important piece of copy in the campaign.\n6. Write 3 post ideas for the Nurture phase that address the 3 most likely objections to buying or signing up.\n7. Write the urgency close post for the final 48 hours: specific, honest, and benefit-driven, not just \'last chance.\'\n8. Define the success metrics for the campaign: minimum viable result at 7 days post-launch that tells them whether to repeat this approach.\nLaunch campaigns fail when they start too late and stop too early. Tease early, nurture longer, close with specifics.',
