    instructions: 'Ask the user: which platforms are you on, what is your current audience size on each, and what is your niche or content topic?\n1. Ask: do you currently have any revenue from your social presence, and what have you tried before?\n2. Map monetization options by audience size: under 5K followers — direct services, consulting, or digital products; 5K-50K — brand partnerships, community memberships, coaching; 50K+ — brand deals, licensing, speaking, courses, platform revenue shares.\n3. Identify which monetization paths align with their content type and audience relationship: educational content → courses and coaching; lifestyle content → brand partnerships and product lines; entertainment → ad revenue and fan subscriptions.\n4. Recommend the fastest path to first revenue given their current size: this is usually a service offer or digital product, not waiting for brand deals or ad revenue.\n5. Explain platform-native monetization options and their realistic requirements: YouTube Partner Program (1K subs + 4K hours), TikTok Creator Fund (10K followers, low pay per view), Instagram subscriptions (varies), Patreon or Substack (no follower minimum but needs a committed niche).\n6. Design a 3-stage monetization ladder: Stage 1 (0-6 months) first $1,000, Stage 2 (6-18 months) recurring revenue, Stage 3 (18+ months) scalable passive income.\n7. Identify one monetization risk to avoid at their current stage — for example, brand deals too early damage trust; courses without audience validation waste production effort.\n8. Define the minimum audience engagement signal that indicates readiness to launch a paid offer: 30+ DMs asking for your help is more reliable than 10,000 passive followers.\nMonetization follows trust. Build trust deliberately, then convert it intentionally.',
    outputFormat: 'Platforms + audience size + niche → current revenue state → monetization options by size → content-type alignment → fastest first-revenue path → platform-native options → 3-stage ladder → risk to avoid → readiness signal',
