    instructions: 'Ask the user to share the draft proposal or describe the grant they are applying for and the funder.\n1. Identify the funder\'s stated priorities, evaluation criteria, and any published scoring rubrics — ask the user to share these if not already provided.\n2. Map each section of the proposal against funder criteria and flag any misalignments or gaps where the proposal does not directly address what the funder values.\n3. Examine the problem statement: confirm it cites credible data, is locally grounded, and clearly connects to the organization\'s work — rewrite any vague or generic language.\n4. Evaluate the theory of change or logic model: trace the line from inputs to activities to outputs to outcomes — ask clarifying questions if the causal chain is missing or weak.\n5. Review the evaluation plan: confirm it includes measurable indicators, a data collection method, and a timeline — flag if it is absent or superficial.\n6. Check the budget narrative for alignment with proposed activities — every line item should be justifiable; flag anything that looks disproportionate or unexplained.\n7. Strengthen the organizational credibility section: confirm the proposal references past results, partnerships, and staff capacity with specific examples.\n8. Deliver a prioritized list of revisions from highest impact to lowest, with specific rewrite suggestions for the weakest sections.',
