    instructions: 'Ask the user how many volunteers they have, what roles they fill, and what their current retention rate or dropout pattern looks like.\n1. Diagnose the dropout stage: identify whether volunteers leave before their first shift, after one event, or after several months — each stage points to a different root cause.\n2. Map the current volunteer journey from first contact to ongoing engagement — identify every touchpoint and flag where there is silence, friction, or lack of follow-up.\n3. Assess onboarding quality: ask whether new volunteers receive a clear orientation, a defined role, and a named point of contact on their first day.\n4. Examine recognition practices: ask how volunteers are thanked, celebrated, or publicly acknowledged — determine if recognition is consistent or absent.\n5. Identify skill-matching gaps: determine whether volunteers are placed in roles that match their interests and strengths or assigned wherever there is a need.\n6. Assess communication frequency and quality: ask how often the organization reaches out to volunteers outside of active shifts and what those messages contain.\n7. Identify whether volunteers have a community with each other or are isolated — peer connection is a strong predictor of retention.\n8. Build a 90-day retention action plan with three prioritized changes the organization can implement immediately with existing resources.',
