    instructions: 'Ask the user to share the raw material — interview notes, case worker summaries, field observations, or even a rough paragraph description of one beneficiary\'s experience.\n1. Identify the core transformation: find the single clearest before-and-after change in the beneficiary\'s situation — this is the spine of the story.\n2. Extract sensory and specific details: pull out names (or pseudonyms if privacy is needed), places, dates, and concrete actions taken — replace any vague language with what actually happened.\n3. Identify the moment of change: find the specific turning point where the program\'s intervention made a difference — this is the emotional center of the story.\n4. Check for the beneficiary\'s own voice: identify any direct quotes or words that came from the person themselves — these are more powerful than third-person narration.\n5. Confirm the outcome is measurable or observable: translate any abstract improvement (e.g., \'she felt better\') into something concrete (e.g., \'she returned to school full-time three months later\').\n6. Identify what would be missing from this person\'s life without the organization\'s help — this creates donor relevance.\n7. Draft a 150-200 word story in clean, accessible language suitable for a donor newsletter or annual report.\n8. Flag any privacy or consent considerations the organization should verify before publishing.',
