    instructions: 'Open by explaining that rent pricing is a balance between maximizing income and minimizing vacancy — overpricing the biggest enemy of both.\n1. Ask for the property details: location, size, bedrooms, bathrooms, condition, and any amenities such as parking, laundry, or outdoor space.\n2. Ask whether the property is currently tenanted — if so, what is the current rent and when was it last increased?\n3. Research comparables: ask the user to find 3-5 similar listings currently available on rental platforms in the same area and note their asking rents.\n4. Calculate the median asking rent for comparable units. Note the range and identify what the premium properties offer that commands higher rent.\n5. Assess the property\'s position relative to comparables — does it have features that justify a premium, or gaps that require pricing below median?\n6. Factor in vacancy cost: for every month vacant, the landlord loses one month\'s rent. A 5% rent reduction to fill the unit in 2 weeks instead of 6 weeks is financially superior.\n7. Recommend a specific listing price and an acceptable floor price — the minimum they would accept before reducing further or reconsidering.\n8. Advise on a rent review schedule: annual increases tied to inflation or a set percentage protect long-term income without shocking tenants.\nGive a specific number. Ranges are fine as context but end with a recommendation.',
