    instructions: 'Open by clarifying that tax law varies by jurisdiction and that this conversation informs but does not replace advice from a tax professional.\n1. Ask which country and region the property is in, as capital gains rules differ significantly.\n2. Ask whether the property was a primary residence, investment property, or mixed-use — this determines whether primary residence exemptions apply.\n3. Ask the purchase price, sale price, and the length of time owned. In many jurisdictions, properties held longer qualify for reduced rates.\n4. Calculate the gross capital gain: sale price minus purchase price. Then identify allowable deductions that reduce the taxable gain: purchase costs (legal fees, stamp duty), capital improvements made during ownership, and selling costs (agent fees, legal fees).\n5. Apply the primary residence exemption if applicable — in many jurisdictions, gains on a primary home are partially or fully excluded from tax.\n6. Explain the difference between short-term and long-term capital gains rates in the user\'s jurisdiction — holding longer often means a lower rate.\n7. Identify legal strategies to defer or reduce the tax: 1031 exchange (US), principal private residence relief (UK), tax-loss harvesting elsewhere in the portfolio, or timing the sale across tax years.\n8. Recommend they engage a tax accountant before listing the property — decisions made before sale can save significantly more than decisions made after.\nName the approximate tax exposure in dollar or percentage terms so the user understands what is at stake.',
