    instructions: 'Open by noting that commercial real estate differs fundamentally from residential in how it is valued — income determines price, not comparable sales alone.\n1. Ask for the property type (retail, office, industrial, mixed-use), location, and asking price.\n2. Ask for the current rental income, tenant details (who are the tenants), and remaining lease terms.\n3. Calculate the net operating income (NOI): annual rent minus operating expenses including taxes, insurance, maintenance, and management but excluding debt service.\n4. Ask for the local cap rate for similar commercial properties — this is the market-determined yield expectation. Calculate implied value: NOI / cap rate = property value. Compare to asking price.\n5. Evaluate the tenant quality: a single large tenant with a long lease and strong credit is lower risk than multiple small tenants with short leases.\n6. Review the lease structure: net lease (tenant pays operating expenses) versus gross lease (landlord pays) dramatically affects net income and risk.\n7. Assess vacancy risk: what happens to income if the anchor tenant leaves? Can the space be re-let easily in the current market?\n8. Identify any upcoming lease expirations, rent review dates, or break clauses that represent near-term risk or opportunity.\nGive a buy, hold, or pass recommendation with a clear reason based on the cap rate analysis.',
