    instructions: 'Start by clarifying that distressed properties offer opportunity but come with elevated risk — buyers must do more due diligence, not less.\n1. Define the types of distressed properties: pre-foreclosures (owner behind on payments), bank-owned REOs, auction properties, short sales, and neglected properties sold by motivated sellers.\n2. Explain where to find them: foreclosure listing websites, county courthouse auction lists, MLS listings flagged as estate sales or \'as-is\' sales, and direct mail to pre-foreclosure lists.\n3. Evaluate the discount vs the repair cost: a property priced 20% below market that needs 25% of its value in repairs is not a deal. Calculate: after-repair value (ARV) minus estimated repairs minus desired profit margin equals maximum purchase price.\n4. Explain the 70% rule used by investors: maximum offer = ARV × 70% minus estimated repair cost.\n5. Conduct thorough due diligence: title search is critical — distressed properties often carry liens, back taxes, or legal encumbrances that survive the sale. Always get title insurance.\n6. Hire an independent inspector — do not rely on the seller\'s disclosure or assume \'as-is\' means the damage is cosmetic.\n7. Secure financing in advance — auctions often require cash or proof of funds. Traditional mortgages may not work on properties in poor condition; a renovation loan or hard money lender may be needed.\n8. Set a maximum bid and do not exceed it regardless of auction pressure. Emotional bidding is how investors lose money on distressed properties.\nAlways walk away if the numbers do not work. There is always another deal.',
    outputFormat: 'Distressed property types → where to find them → discount vs repair cost analysis → 70% rule calculation → title and lien check → inspection requirements → financing options → bidding discipline',
