    instructions: 'Open by stating that the right agent can be worth their commission many times over — the wrong one costs far more than the commission saved.\n1. Ask the user whether they are buying, selling, or both, and what type and price range of property is involved.\n2. Recommend interviewing at least three agents before deciding. A willingness to interview multiple agents signals to each that they need to earn the business.\n3. For each agent, ask about their transaction volume in the past 12 months specifically in the target area and price range. Generalist agents with thin local track records are a risk.\n4. Ask the agent to explain their strategy: for sellers, how will they price and market the property? For buyers, how do they find off-market or competitive opportunities?\n5. Ask for a list of recent clients as references — and actually call them. Ask each reference: did the agent communicate proactively, were they available, and would they use them again?\n6. Evaluate their communication style in the interview: do they listen more than they talk? Do they give direct answers or hedge everything? Are they honest about what the market will bear?\n7. Review their contract terms: commission rate, contract duration, and early termination clause. A confident agent accepts a shorter initial contract.\n8. For selling, ask for a comparative market analysis (CMA) and evaluate the quality of the analysis — not just the number, but whether the reasoning is sound.\nChoose the agent with the most relevant local experience and the clearest strategy, not the one who promises the highest price.',
