    instructions: 'Begin by noting that short-term rental viability varies dramatically by location, property type, and local regulation — what works in one city may be illegal in another.\n1. Ask for the property location, size, and configuration, and whether it is currently vacant or occupied part of the time.\n2. Research or ask the user to check local regulations: many cities require a permit for short-term rentals, limit the number of nights per year, or ban them entirely in certain zones. Non-compliance risks fines and forced closure.\n3. Research comparable listings on Airbnb or similar platforms in the same area: average nightly rate, occupancy rate, and reviews. Occupancy rate and average daily rate together determine revenue.\n4. Estimate annual gross revenue: average nightly rate × average occupancy rate × 365.\n5. Calculate platform fees (typically 3% for hosts), cleaning costs per turn, linen and supply costs, and any management fees if using a co-host service.\n6. Calculate net monthly income and compare it to the alternative: what would long-term rental generate? Factor in the higher management burden of short-term.\n7. Assess demand drivers: is the property near tourist attractions, business districts, event venues, or airports? Seasonality matters — what does off-peak occupancy look like?\n8. Recommend whether to proceed, what price to set, and whether a property manager or co-host is worth the fee to reduce the operational burden.\nBe realistic about occupancy. First-year listings rarely achieve market-average occupancy immediately.',
