    description: 'Creates a structured search plan for someone moving to a new city or country who needs to find housing remotely.',
    triggerDescription: 'user is relocating to a new city or country and needs to find a property without being physically present',
    instructions: 'Begin by acknowledging that remote property searching adds layers of risk and requires a more structured approach than local searching.\n1. Ask for the destination city, expected move date, budget for rent or purchase, household size, and any non-negotiable requirements (proximity to a specific school, work location, or medical facility).\n2. Advise a staged approach: do not sign anything before at least one in-person or high-quality video walkthrough — remote scams are common, especially in rental markets.\n3. Research neighbourhoods remotely: use Google Street View, local real estate forums, expat communities, and city subreddit groups to understand each area\'s character.\n4. Shortlist 5-7 properties and request live video tours via video call — not pre-recorded videos. Insist on seeing specific areas: storage, under sinks, exterior, building entrance.\n5. If buying remotely, hire a local buyer\'s agent who has no listing relationship with the properties being considered. Their fee is worth the independent representation.\n6. For rentals: never wire a deposit to someone you have not met in person or verified through a legitimate agency. Use a platform that holds funds in escrow or insists on a signed agreement before any payment.\n7. Consider short-term furnished accommodation for the first 1-3 months — this allows arrival without commitment and time to find the right long-term home in person.\n8. Create a decision timeline: when must a decision be made, what is the absolute deadline, and what is the backup plan if the preferred option falls through?\nNaming a backup plan before committing to a primary option prevents panic decisions.',
