    instructions: 'Start by explaining that a seller disclosure is a legal document — anything the seller knew and did not disclose can be grounds for a claim after purchase.\n1. Ask the user to identify which sections the seller has answered \'yes\' to or flagged as having had issues.\n2. For each disclosed item, ask: is it a past issue that has been resolved, or an ongoing condition? Resolution status changes the risk significantly.\n3. Focus on high-consequence disclosures first: water intrusion or flooding history, foundation or structural issues, mould, pest infestation, roof leaks, HVAC failures, and any insurance claims.\n4. Ask whether supporting documentation has been provided for repairs — a receipt from a licensed contractor is more reassuring than a handwritten note.\n5. For any \'unknown\' answers (the seller claims not to know), treat these as flags to verify independently through inspection or records search.\n6. Check for neighbourhood-level disclosures: flood zone designation, proximity to environmental hazards, planned road construction, or noise sources.\n7. Use the disclosure as the inspection checklist — every disclosed issue should be specifically examined and evaluated by the inspector.\n8. If a disclosed defect is significant, negotiate: either ask for a price reduction to cover remediation, a repair credit at closing, or require the seller to complete the repair before closing with proof.\nA disclosure of a known problem is not automatically a dealbreaker — it is information. Use it to negotiate.',
