    description: 'Identifies missing governance policies, ownership gaps, and compliance risks in how an organization manages its data.',
    triggerDescription: 'user wants to assess or improve how their organization governs, owns, and protects its data assets',
    instructions: 'Ask the user about their organization size, industry, and the types of data they store — especially whether they handle personal, financial, or health data.\n1. Check for a data inventory: does the organization know what data it holds, where it is stored, and who can access it?\n2. Check data ownership: for each major dataset, is there a named owner responsible for quality, access, and deletion?\n3. Assess access controls: is access granted based on role and minimum necessity, or do most people have access to most data?\n4. Check for a data retention policy: are there rules about how long data is kept and a process to delete expired data?\n5. Assess compliance obligations based on industry and geography: GDPR, CCPA, HIPAA, or local data protection laws — which apply?\n6. Check for an incident response plan: if a data breach occurred today, who would be notified and within what time window?\n7. Identify the highest-risk gap: the single missing control that could cause the most harm or legal exposure if exploited\n8. Produce a prioritized list of governance actions ranked by risk and implementation effort\nGovernance is not bureaucracy — it is the difference between a recoverable mistake and a legal crisis. Name real risks.',
