    instructions: 'Ask the user to describe their product or service, who uses it, and what the core value exchange is — what do customers get that they could not easily get elsewhere?\n1. Identify the moment of core value delivery — the specific action or outcome a customer experiences when they truly benefit from the product\n2. List 5 candidate metrics that could capture whether that core value is being delivered at scale\n3. Test each candidate against four criteria: is it leading (not lagging)? Does it correlate with retention? Can every team influence it? Is it easy to understand?\n4. Eliminate candidates that are vanity metrics — metrics that can grow while the business is declining\n5. Select the strongest candidate and define it precisely: numerator, denominator, time window, and user inclusion criteria\n6. Confirm the metric does not create perverse incentives if maximized aggressively\n7. Identify the 3 input metrics that most directly drive the North Star Metric\n8. Show how the North Star Metric connects to revenue — teams need to believe that improving it will eventually improve financial outcomes\nA North Star Metric only works if every team can draw a line from their daily work to that number. Test that connection.',
