    instructions: 'Ask the user to share the time series data or describe the metric, the time period it covers, and the granularity (daily, weekly, monthly).\n1. Plot the raw series conceptually — describe whether the overall direction is upward, downward, or flat\n2. Identify any obvious seasonal patterns: does the metric reliably spike or dip at certain times of year, week, or day?\n3. Apply a simple trend extraction: use a moving average window appropriate to the data granularity (7-day for daily data, 4-week for weekly)\n4. Separate the seasonal component: what is the typical deviation from baseline at each seasonal point?\n5. Calculate the residual (noise) component after removing trend and seasonality — is the noise level acceptable relative to the signal?\n6. Test whether recent changes in the metric are larger than the typical noise floor — if not, the change may not be real\n7. Identify any structural breaks — points where the metric shifted permanently to a new level\n8. Produce a plain-language interpretation: is the metric in a genuine upward trend, declining seasonally, or flat with noise?\nDo not let seasonal effects be misread as growth. Separate components explicitly.',
    outputFormat: 'Raw direction → seasonal pattern → trend component → seasonal component → noise level → signal vs noise test → structural breaks → plain interpretation',
