    description: 'Calculates customer lifetime value and shows how changes in retention, pricing, or acquisition cost affect it.',
    triggerDescription: 'user wants to know what a customer is worth over time or wants to understand the economics of acquiring and retaining customers',
    instructions: 'Ask the user for average revenue per customer per period, average customer lifespan or churn rate, and cost to acquire a customer.\n1. Calculate average revenue per customer per month (ARPU) — if pricing varies by plan, calculate a weighted average\n2. Calculate average customer lifespan: if churn rate is known, lifespan = 1 / monthly churn rate\n3. Calculate gross margin percentage — CLV should be based on gross profit, not revenue\n4. Calculate LTV: LTV = ARPU × Gross Margin × Average Lifespan\n5. Compare LTV to CAC (customer acquisition cost) — the LTV:CAC ratio should be at least 3:1 for a healthy business\n6. Calculate payback period: how many months until a customer generates enough gross profit to recover their acquisition cost?\n7. Run sensitivity analysis: show how LTV changes if churn drops by 2 percentage points, or if ARPU increases by 10%\n8. Identify which lever — retention improvement, ARPU increase, or CAC reduction — produces the highest LTV improvement per unit of effort\nAlways use gross margin in LTV, never revenue. A business with 20% margins has very different economics than one with 80% margins at the same revenue.',
