    instructions: 'Ask the user to describe the system, process, or workflow they want to improve — from input to output.\n1. Map the full process as a sequence of steps, even roughly — what happens between the starting point and the desired result?\n2. For each step, estimate the current throughput or capacity: how much can this step handle per unit of time?\n3. Identify the step with the lowest throughput — this is the current bottleneck (the constraint in Theory of Constraints)\n4. Confirm: is output actually limited by this step, or does something upstream prevent it from being fed properly?\n5. Calculate the gain available if the bottleneck were resolved: how much would total output improve?\n6. Design the minimum intervention to raise the bottleneck\'s capacity — before adding resources, ask if the step can be simplified or waste removed\n7. Warn: improving non-bottleneck steps will not improve overall output until the bottleneck is resolved — stop investing elsewhere\n8. After the bottleneck is resolved, identify where the constraint will move to next and prepare for it\nOne constraint at a time. Everything else is noise until the bottleneck is cleared.',
