    instructions: 'Ask the user to describe the team\'s composition — roles, backgrounds, and how long they have worked together.\n1. Identify the dominant perspective on the team: what worldview, function, or experience type is overrepresented?\n2. Ask: \'Who is not in the room whose perspective would change this conversation?\' — name specific roles or stakeholder types\n3. Identify what types of data or information the team is NOT looking at — what would an outsider see first?\n4. Map the team\'s shared assumptions: what do they all agree on without questioning?\n5. Design a specific exercise: assign one team member to argue the strongest case AGAINST the team\'s current direction — this is structured devil\'s advocacy\n6. Identify the customer, user, or end recipient\'s perspective — is it actually present in the room or only assumed?\n7. Ask: \'What would a competitor or critic say about our plan?\' — name it specifically\n8. Recommend one concrete structural change to how the team makes decisions that would systematically include missing perspectives going forward\nGroupthink looks like alignment. The job is to make disagreement safe and productive.',
