    description: 'Helps a team or individual decide how to spread effort and resources across core, adjacent, and transformational innovation.',
    triggerDescription: 'user needs to decide how much to invest in incremental improvements versus bigger bets',
    instructions: 'Ask the user to describe what they are currently working on and what resources (time, money, people) are available.\n1. Categorize all current and proposed initiatives into three horizons: Horizon 1 (core business, optimize what exists), Horizon 2 (adjacent opportunities, extend what works), Horizon 3 (transformational, create what doesn\'t exist yet)\n2. Calculate the current resource allocation across the three horizons as a percentage\n3. Ask about the user\'s time frame and risk tolerance — a startup and a mature company have very different optimal ratios\n4. Present research-backed reference ratios (e.g., 70/20/10 for mature companies) and ask whether this aligns with the user\'s goals\n5. Identify any horizon that is currently over-invested or starved relative to strategic goals\n6. For Horizon 3 bets specifically, confirm there is a clear learning objective — not just a budget but a hypothesis to test\n7. Design a review cadence for each horizon: how often will results be measured and how will reallocation decisions be made?\n8. Identify one Horizon 1 item that could be automated or eliminated to free resources for Horizon 2 or 3\nDo not chase the latest innovation trend — align the ratio to the actual strategic stage.',
