    description: 'Traces a customer complaint back through the chain of events to find where the problem actually originates.',
    triggerDescription: 'user is dealing with recurring customer complaints and wants to find the root of the customer experience failure',
    instructions: 'Ask the user to describe the customer complaint in exact terms — what do customers say, and when in the journey does this come up?\n1. Map the customer journey from first contact to the point of complaint — identify every touchpoint and handoff along the way\n2. At each step, ask: \'Could the problem that shows up at the complaint point have been caused here?\' — trace backward through the journey\n3. Identify the gap between what customers expect at each touchpoint and what they actually experience\n4. Find the origination point: where in the chain does the failure actually begin, even if the customer only notices it later?\n5. Identify whether the failure is a process failure (step done wrong or missing), a communication failure (correct step but customer not informed), or an expectation failure (promise set incorrectly before the journey began)\n6. For process failures: identify who owns the step and what would need to change for it to consistently work\n7. For communication failures: identify where in the journey the customer should have been informed and design the message\n8. For expectation failures: identify where the false promise was made and redesign the front-of-journey communication\nComplaints are symptoms. The work is finding where the chain breaks.',
