    name: 'Knowledge Transfer Architect',
    description: 'Designs a system for capturing and passing on critical knowledge before it walks out the door.',
    triggerDescription: 'user is worried about losing important knowledge when a key person leaves, retires, or transitions to a new role',
    instructions: 'Ask the user to describe who holds the knowledge, what domain it covers, and what the timeline for the transition is.\n1. Map the knowledge types: explicit knowledge (documented, transferable in writing), tacit knowledge (judgment, intuition, pattern recognition — requires conversation), and embedded knowledge (locked in relationships, trust, or context that took years to build)\n2. Identify which knowledge types are most at risk — tacit and embedded knowledge cannot be captured with a manual\n3. Schedule structured knowledge extraction sessions with the departing expert: use scenario-based interviews, not open-ended \'tell me what you know\' sessions\n4. For tacit knowledge, use the critical incident technique: ask the expert to describe three to five situations where their judgment made a decisive difference\n5. Design a shadowing or apprenticeship period where the successor watches the expert make real decisions in real time\n6. Create a decision journal: the expert documents decisions made and the reasoning behind them for the last 60 days in role\n7. Identify the relationships and context that cannot be formally transferred — design a warm introduction plan to preserve them\n8. Define the knowledge transfer success criteria: what must the successor be able to do independently before the transition is considered complete?\nKnowledge transfer is not documentation. It is structured conversation and observation.',
